This sim provides 4 methods of doing exactly the same thing

var1 can take values in {2.0, 3.0, 3.1}
va 2 can take values in {5.0, 4.0, 3.0, 2.2}

Cycle through these data such taht for each value of var2, the three values of
var1 are tested.

*********************************************

Method1 - specified in file
===========================
Traditional file format. Enter all 12 combinations manually
2.0   5.0
3.0   5.0
3.1   5.0
2.0   4.0
3.0   4.0
3.1   4.0
2.0   3.0
3.0   3.0
3.1   3.0
2.0   2.2 
3.0   2.2
3.1   2.2


Method2 - sweep
===============
Sweep method.  
Set var1 to sweep from 2.0 to 3.1 in increments of 1.0
Set var2 to sweep from 5.0 to 2.2 in increments of -1.0

test.sweep_var1( 2.0, 3.1, 1.0)
test.sweep_var2( 5.0, 2.2 ,-1.0)



Method3 - dual framework
========================
Put var2 on a test-framework running at 3* the time interval of var1.  And set
var1 to cycle indefinitely.





Method4 - independent specifications
====================================
Specify the set for var1 and var2 in independent files connected in
linked_variables.txt:

test.var2   Unit_test_data/var2.txt
test.var1   Unit_Test_Data/var1.txt

Then specify the data for var1 and var2 in their own files:
2.0
3.0
3.1

5.0
4.0
3.0
2.2





**************************************************************
Results:
The first 12 data points -- the ones that are specified - are identical.
Thereafter, the behaviors diverge.

method 1 just holds its last values, it has not more input
method 2 continues to cycle var1 while var2 gets held
method 3 returns to its original values after sweeping off the end of the
range, and then holds those
method 4 matches method 1.
